why: Primary baseline: Wage equation of VAR(2) system. L1 income coefficient = 1.108.
Primary baseline: Price equation of VAR(2) system. L1 income coefficient = 0.291. Key result of paper.
Primary baseline: Sales growth equation of VAR(2) system. L1 income coefficient = 0.387.
Primary baseline: Construction rate equation of VAR(2) system. L1 income coefficient = 0.037.
Primary baseline: Population growth equation of VAR(2) system. L1 income coefficient = 0.074.
VAR(1) instead of VAR(2). Coefficient collapses to ~0 (0.0005; p=0.99). Shows lag structure is critical.
VAR(3) instead of VAR(2). Coefficient 0.315; similar magnitude to baseline.
VAR(4) instead of VAR(2). Coefficient 0.244; somewhat smaller but still significant.
Pooled OLS (no city FE). Coefficient 0.321; very similar to LSDV baseline.
Two-way FE (city + time). Coefficient 0.291; identical to baseline (time FE already demeaned).
City-clustered SEs. Same coefficient 0.291; larger SE but still highly significant.
Robust heteroskedasticity-consistent SEs. Same coefficient; robust to heteroskedasticity.
HAC kernel SEs. Same coefficient; HAC SEs substantially larger (0.104 vs 0.040) but still significant at 1%.
Random effects estimation. Coefficient 0.321; very close to LSDV suggesting FE appropriate.
First differences estimation. Coefficient 0.282; close to baseline.
4-variable VAR dropping sales growth. Coefficient 0.307; robust to excluding sales.
4-variable VAR dropping construction. Coefficient 0.305; robust to excluding construction.
4-variable VAR dropping population growth. Coefficient 0.282; robust to excluding population.
Bivariate VAR (income and price only). Coefficient 0.354; similar magnitude without controls.
Trivariate VAR (income/price/sales). Coefficient 0.309; robust to reduced variable set.
Trivariate VAR (income/price/construction). Coefficient 0.306; robust to reduced variable set.
6-variable VAR adding construction wage. Coefficient 0.323; robust to additional variable. Smaller sample (98 cities).
6-variable VAR adding construction labor. Coefficient 0.266; somewhat smaller but robust.
Rent replaces price as outcome. Coefficient 0.112 -- different outcome variable tests a distinct relationship.
Growth rates transformation of variables. Coefficient 0.333; similar magnitude in differenced form.
Coastal cities subsample (31 cities). Coefficient 0.110; much smaller than baseline; p=0.109.
Inland cities subsample (47 cities). Coefficient 0.320; larger than baseline.
Sunbelt cities subsample (28 cities). Coefficient 0.304; close to baseline.
Non-sunbelt cities (78 cities). Coefficient 0.235; slightly smaller.
Non-coastal cities (75 cities). Coefficient 0.378; larger than baseline.
Top 50 cities by population. Coefficient 0.209; smaller but significant.
Bottom 56 cities by population. Coefficient 0.318; close to baseline.
Pre-2000 subsample (1982-1999). Coefficient 0.161; smaller than full period.
Post-1990 subsample (1990-2007). Coefficient 0.186; smaller than full period.
Pre-crisis subsample (1982-2005). Coefficient 0.228; somewhat smaller than baseline.
Shorter panel (1985-2005). Coefficient 0.150; notably smaller.
Drop last 2 years. Coefficient 0.228; identical to pre_crisis as expected.
Early period only (1982-1994). Coefficient 0.065; much smaller and insignificant (p=0.378).
Drop NYC metro area. Coefficient 0.301; nearly identical to baseline.
Drop LA metro area. Coefficient 0.288; nearly identical to baseline.
Drop Chicago metro area. Coefficient 0.292; nearly identical to baseline.
Drop Philadelphia metro area. Coefficient 0.291; nearly identical to baseline.
Drop Dallas metro area. Coefficient 0.291; nearly identical to baseline.
Drop Miami metro area. Coefficient 0.292; nearly identical to baseline.
Winsorize at 1%. Coefficient 0.145; substantially smaller than baseline.
Winsorize at 5%. Coefficient 0.133; substantially smaller than baseline.
Trim 1% tails. Coefficient 0.115; substantially smaller (p=0.026 marginal).
Trim 5% tails. Coefficient 0.043; small and insignificant (p=0.639). Only 1419 obs remain.
Depreciation factor = 0.90. Coefficient 0.290; virtually identical to baseline.
Depreciation factor = 0.93. Coefficient 0.291; virtually identical to baseline.
Depreciation factor = 0.99. Coefficient 0.291; virtually identical to baseline.
Depreciation factor = 0.98. Coefficient 0.291; virtually identical to baseline.
Original 2014 data (vs. 2016 update used as baseline). Coefficient 0.291; identical.
Price effect on wages -- extracts different parameter (L1_px) from baseline VAR. Different treatment variable.
Price effect on sales growth -- extracts L1_px from baseline VAR. Different treatment variable.
Price effect on construction rate -- extracts L1_px from baseline VAR. Different treatment variable.
Price effect on population growth -- extracts L1_px from baseline VAR. Different treatment variable.
L2 income coefficient in wage equation -- different parameter (second lag). Tests dynamic structure not baseline effect.
L2 income coefficient in price equation (-0.263). Different parameter from L1 (0.291). Negative sign expected for mean-reversion.
L2 income coefficient in sales growth equation. Different parameter from L1.
L2 income coefficient in construction rate equation. Different parameter from L1.
L2 income coefficient in population growth equation. Different parameter from L1.
Restrict to 98 cities with construction data. Coefficient 0.322; close to baseline.
Construction wage replaces income as treatment. Coefficient 0.030 (p=0.071). Different treatment variable.
Balanced panel verification. Coefficient 0.291; confirms baseline panel is already balanced.
